# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: authorized-protective-eyewear-list
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The **Authorized Protective Eyewear List (APEL)** is a list of protective eyewear tested and approved by the U.S.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The APEL includes spectacles and goggles optimized for different situations.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The APEL was created in 2006 because statistics showed that about 10% of battlefield injuries at that time included eye injuries.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The APEL is updated periodically; it usually contains more than a dozen types of non-prescription and prescription spectacles and goggles for different duty situations and soldier preferences.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] In 2010, the **APEL** was placed under the oversight of the Military Combat Eyewear Protection (MCEP) program under the office of PEO Soldier.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The APEL also includes different styles to accommodate soldier preferences, with the goal of increasing the use of eye protection.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Approved protective eyewear includes both military standard and commercial styles.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Soldiers serve in different situations with different types of risk for eye injury, from ballistic projectiles.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Some styles can accommodate prescription lenses.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Several types of goggles are available because they are optimized for certain purposes, such as regular use, use in vehicles, or use with night vision goggles.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Some fit over regular eyeglasses, some can accommodate prescription lenses, and others are designed for those who do not wear eyeglasses.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Eyewear on the APEL must meet the standards established by the Army Vision Conservation and Readiness Program.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] For ballistic resistance, this program requires that eyewear meet the current ANSI Z87 civilian standard.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Then the U.S. military standard (MIL-PRF-31013) must also be met.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The U.S. civilian standard for protective eyewear was revised in 2010.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The previous version from 2003 was organized by the type of protector.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The Z87.1-2010 version is organized by the type of hazard such as droplet and splash, impact, optical radiation, dust, fine dust, and mist.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Also, the 2003 version specified that protective products be marked as providing “Basic” or “High Impact” protection.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] In the Z87.1-2010 standard, there is no longer a distinction between levels of ballistic protection.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Products are either non-impact or impact protectors.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Products marked as impact protectors must pass all high-impact testing requirements and are marked as “Z87+”.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Non-impact protectors are those which do not pass all high-impact testing requirements and are therefore marked only with “Z87” (no “+” sign).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The U.S. military standard (MIL-PRF-31013), requires (at a minimum) that ballistic eyewear can always withstand a 0.15 caliber, 5.8 grain, T37 shaped projectile at a velocity of 640 to 660 feet per second (approximately 3.8 mm 0.376 g at a velocity of 195 – 201 m/s).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Goggles are required to stop a 17-grain fragment simulating projectile moving at a speed of 550 feet per second (approximately twice the energy impact of spectacles).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] For testing, the velocity of the projectile must be verified using sound or optical chronograph methods.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The eyewear is put on an Alderson 50th percentile male headform.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] A 0.002 inch thick aluminum foil “witness sheet” is placed behind the area of impact.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] This sheet shows whether any small pieces penetrate or come off of the eyewear during the test.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The eyewear being tested is hit one time straight on slightly toward the outside of the center of the lens.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The eyewear fails the test if the aluminum foil witness sheet is punctured or if the eyewear is cracked.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] In addition to ballistic performance, the U.S. military standard includes requirements for optical clarity, protection from UV rays, fit, chemical resistance, and environmental stability (properties won’t be changed by exposure to a range of temperatures or levels of humidity).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Though soldiers are increasingly exposed to explosive threats, there is currently no testing or performance requirements for blast resistance of approved eyewear.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Safety glasses, sunglasses and goggles that claim to meet ballistic safety standards are widely available.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Some can accommodate prescription lenses.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Although not required, it is recommended that all eyewear meet ANSI Z87.1, but for ballistic protective eyewear it is required that it meets military standards for impact protection (MIL-DTL-43511D clause 3.5.10 for goggles and visors and MIL-PRF31013 clause 3.5.1.1 for spectacles).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Though these standards have been very commonly used especially by NATO forces, an update on MCEPS of January 2013 now reference these clauses in MIL-PRF-32432.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Ballistic sunglasses or prescription eyeglasses must meet the same requirements.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] In brief, the U.S. military standard requires that ballistic eyewear must be able to withstand up to a 3.8 mm (.15 caliber) projectile at 195 m/s (640 ft/s)) for spectacles and 5.6 mm (.22 caliber) projectile at 168–171 m/s (550–560 ft/s) for goggles.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] The European standard identifies four levels of impact protection.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Manufacturers offer a variety of styles and colors to meet different needs and preferences.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Some make claims of superior side protection, comfort, anti-fog coatings, interchangeable lenses, transition lenses, etc.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] At least one product from more than a half dozen manufacturers are listed on the U.S.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Army's Authorized Protective Eyewear List (APEL).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Some options, including the Wiley X PT-1 and Talon as well as Revision's Sawfly and the Desert Locust Goggle can be obtained in prescription lenses that meet the ballistic protection standards.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] In addition to impact requirements, the U.S.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Army requires for its soldiers that ballistic eyewear be functional, reasonably comfortable, not faddish (i.e., no bright colors or distracting designs) and able to be disinfected.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Ballistic eyewear is commercially available for anyone who wishes to buy it.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] People who use ballistic eyewear include those who regularly use firearms or are involved in activities where their eyes or faces may be exposed to small fragments.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] This includes many people who work in manufacturing.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Military personnel may be required to use ballistic eyewear especially when in combat.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Hunters are also frequent users of ballistic eyewear because of the possibility of a ricochet or the recoil of the firearm that may result in injury.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Law enforcement officers also use ballistic eyewear for confrontations.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] There are three standards currently used to test the effectiveness of ballistic eyewear.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Also, the 2003 version specified that protective products be marked as providing "Basic" or "High Impact" protection.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Products marked as impact protectors must pass all high-impact testing requirements and are marked as "Z87+".
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Non-impact protectors are those which do not pass all high-impact testing requirements and are therefore marked only with "Z87" (no "+" sign).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] The U.S. military standard requires (at a minimum) that ballistic eyewear can always withstand a 0.15 caliber, 5.8 grain, T37 shaped projectile at a velocity of 640 to 660 feet per second (approximately 3.8 mm 0.376 g at a velocity of 195 – 201 m/s).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] A 0.002 inch thick aluminum foil "witness sheet" is placed behind the area of impact.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] In addition to ballistic performance, the U.S. military standard includes requirements for optical clarity, protection from UV rays, fit, chemical resistance, and environmental stability (properties won't be changed by exposure to a range of temperatures or levels of humidity).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] The European EN 166 standard identifies four levels of ballistic protection.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] "Increased robustness" (marked S) can withstand a 22 mm steel ball weighing 43 g dropped onto the lens from a height of .38 meters (15 inches).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] "Low energy impact" (marked F) can withstand a 6mm steel ball weighing 0.86 g and traveling at least 45 m/s at the time of impact.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] "Medium energy impact" (marked B) must be able to protect from a 6 mm 0.86 g steel ball with an impact velocity of 120 m/s.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] "High energy impact" (marked A) must be able to protect from a 6 mm 0.86 g steel ball with an impact velocity of 190 m/s.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] The history of protective eyewear goes back to 1880, when P.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Johnson's design used two layers of semi-opaque cloth.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] He had in mind that firemen, furnace-men and others exposed to intense light would use them to reduce the light intensity.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Fullicks bonded several pieces of glass together.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] It seems that another Englishman, John Crane Woods, had safety in mind when he patented the idea of bonding sheets of transparent cellulose nitrate, using Canadian balsam, between two sheets of glass.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] The product was unsuccessful due to expense, poor quality and lack of demand.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] In 1910, Edouard Benedictus, a French chemist, obtained both French and British patents for the manufacturing of laminated safety glass.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Benedictus used gelatin and other adhesives instead of Canadian balsam in the laminated glass.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] During World War I, laminated glass was used to make small, round lenses in gas masks and for windshields in military motor vehicles and aircraft.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] (For a number of recent years, the DuPont chemical company gave a Benedictus Award for the innovative use of laminated glass in architecture.) In the 1940s, manufacturers figured out how to sand and make safety glasses and goggles for welders, construction workers, and the like.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] In the early 1960s the U.S. government sponsored experiments testing the ballistic performance of various plastics and glass for potential use in eyewear, using tests similar to those required by today's U.S. military standard.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] After this time, polycarbonate became the standard material used for ballistic eyewear.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Investigations since this early work have included examining the effects of manufacturing and layering techniques on the ballistic performance of polycarbonates.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] In the early 1970s, Wigglesworth investigated the ballistic resistance of 3 mm. and 2 mm. thicknesses of allyl resin and tempered glass as a function of the diameter of a small steel ball, impact velocity, and curvature of the lens.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] In 1996, Belkin described new ballistic eyewear that also provided improved protection from injuries caused by laser light reaching the eyes.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] Research into improved protection of the eyes from ballistic threats has continued.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] For example, Kelly presented work investigating layered materials to provide protection from 9 mm automatic gunfire, a much greater level of ballistic protection than previously available.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] While they demonstrated a successful concept, they recognized that advances in manufacturability were still needed for such protective eyewear to be affordable and plentiful.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] In 2006 Hartley et al. were awarded a US Patent for Eyewear for ballistic and light protection.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistic-eye-wear] The invention was not for new protective materials but for a system that would allow the easier interchange of lenses between various types of protective devices, such as glasses, goggles and face shields.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] A **ballistic body** is a free-moving body with momentum, which can be subject to forces such as those exerted by pressurized gases from a gun barrel or a propelling nozzle, normal force by rifling, and gravity and air drag during flight.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The earliest known ballistic projectiles were stones, spears, and the throwing stick.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The oldest evidence of stone-tipped projectiles, which may or may not have been propelled by a bow (cf. atlatl), dating to c.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] 280,000 years ago, were found in Ethiopia, present day East Africa.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The oldest evidence of the use of bows to shoot arrows dates to about 10,000 years ago; it is based on pinewood arrows found in the Ahrensburg valley north of Hamburg.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] They had shallow grooves on the base, indicating that they were shot from a bow.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The oldest bow so far recovered is about 8,000 years old, found in the Holmegård swamp in Denmark.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Archery seems to have arrived in the Americas with the Arctic small tool tradition, about 4,500 years ago.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The first devices identified as guns appeared in China around 1000 AD, and by the 12th century the technology was spreading through the rest of Asia, and into Europe by the 13th century.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Galileo established the principle of compound motion in 1638, using the principle to derive the parabolic form of the ballistic trajectory.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Ballistics was put on a solid scientific and mathematical basis by Isaac Newton, with the publication of Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica in 1687.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] This gave mathematical laws of motion and gravity which for the first time made it possible to successfully predict trajectories.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The word *ballistics* comes from the Greek βάλλειν *ballein*, meaning "to throw".
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] A projectile is any object projected into space (empty or not) by the exertion of a force.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Although any object in motion through space (for example a thrown baseball) is a projectile, the term most commonly refers to a weapon.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Mathematical equations of motion are used to analyze projectile trajectory.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Examples of projectiles include balls, arrows, bullets, artillery shells, wingless rockets, etc.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Throwing is the launching of a projectile by hand.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Although some other animals can throw, humans are unusually good throwers due to their high dexterity and good timing capabilities, and it is believed that this is an evolved trait.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Evidence of human throwing dates back 2 million years.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The 145 km/h (90 mph) throwing speed found in many athletes far exceeds the speed at which chimpanzees can throw things, which is about 32 km/h (20 mph).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] This ability reflects the ability of the human shoulder muscles and tendons to store elasticity until it is needed to propel an object.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] A sling is a projectile weapon typically used to throw a blunt projectile such as a stone, clay or lead "sling-bullet".
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] A sling has a small cradle or *pouch* in the middle of two lengths of cord.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The *sling stone* is placed in the pouch.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The middle finger or thumb is placed through a loop on the end of one cord, and a tab at the end of the other cord is placed between the thumb and forefinger.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The sling is swung in an arc, and the tab released at a precise moment.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] This frees the projectile to fly to the target.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] A bow is a flexible piece of material which shoots aerodynamic projectiles called arrows.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The arrow is perhaps the first lethal projectile ever described in discussion of ballistics.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] A string joins the two ends and when the string is drawn back, the ends of the stick are flexed.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] When the string is released, the potential energy of the flexed stick is transformed into the velocity of the arrow.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Archery is the art or sport of shooting arrows from bows.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] A catapult is a device used to launch a projectile a great distance without the aid of explosive devices – particularly various types of ancient and medieval siege engines.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The catapult has been used since ancient times, because it was proven to be one of the most effective mechanisms during warfare.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The word "catapult" comes from the Latin *catapulta*, which in turn comes from the Greek καταπέλτης (*katapeltēs*), itself from κατά (*kata*), "against” and πάλλω (*pallō*), "to toss, to hurl".
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Catapults were invented by the ancient Greeks.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] A gun is a normally tubular weapon or other device designed to discharge projectiles or other material.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The projectile may be solid, liquid, gas, or energy and may be free, as with bullets and artillery shells, or captive as with Taser probes and whaling harpoons.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The means of projection varies according to design but is usually effected by the action of gas pressure, either produced through the rapid combustion of a propellant or compressed and stored by mechanical means, operating on the projectile inside an open-ended tube in the fashion of a piston.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The confined gas accelerates the movable projectile down the length of the tube imparting sufficient velocity to sustain the projectile's travel once the action of the gas ceases at the end of the tube or muzzle.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Alternatively, acceleration via electromagnetic field generation may be employed in which case the tube may be dispensed with and a guide rail substituted.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] A weapons engineer or armourer who applies the scientific principles of ballistics to design cartridges is often called a **ballistician**.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] A rocket is a missile, spacecraft, aircraft or other vehicle that obtains thrust from a rocket engine.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Rocket engine exhaust is formed entirely from propellants carried within the rocket before use.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Rocket engines work by action and reaction.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Rocket engines push rockets forward simply by throwing their exhaust backwards extremely fast.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] While comparatively inefficient for low speed use, rockets are relatively lightweight and powerful, capable of generating large accelerations and of attaining extremely high speeds with reasonable efficiency.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Rockets are not reliant on the atmosphere and work very well in space.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Rockets for military and recreational uses date back to at least 13th century China.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Significant scientific, interplanetary and industrial use did not occur until the 20th century, when rocketry was the enabling technology for the Space Age, including setting foot on the Moon.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Rockets are now used for fireworks, weaponry, ejection seats, launch vehicles for artificial satellites, human spaceflight, and space exploration.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Chemical rockets are the most common type of high performance rocket and they typically create their exhaust by the combustion of rocket propellant.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Chemical rockets store a large amount of energy in an easily released form, and can be very dangerous.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] However, careful design, testing, construction and use minimizes risks.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Internal ballistics (also interior ballistics), a sub-field of ballistics, is the study of the propulsion of a projectile.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] In guns, internal ballistics covers the time from the propellant's ignition until the projectile exits the gun barrel.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The study of internal ballistics is important to designers and users of firearms of all types, from small-bore rifles and pistols, to high-tech artillery.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] For rocket propelled projectiles, internal ballistics covers the period during which a rocket engine is providing thrust.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Transitional ballistics, also known as intermediate ballistics, is the study of a projectile's behavior from the time it leaves the muzzle until the pressure behind the projectile is equalized, so it lies between internal ballistics and external ballistics.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] External ballistics is the part of the science of ballistics that deals with the behaviour of a non-powered projectile in flight.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] External ballistics is frequently associated with firearms, and deals with the unpowered free-flight phase of the bullet after it exits the gun barrel and before it hits the target, so it lies between transitional ballistics and terminal ballistics.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] However, external ballistics is also concerned with the free-flight of rockets and other projectiles, such as balls, arrows etc.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Terminal ballistics is the study of the behavior and effects of a projectile when it hits its target.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Terminal ballistics is relevant both for small caliber projectiles as well as for large caliber projectiles (fired from artillery).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] The study of extremely high velocity impacts is still very new and is as yet mostly applied to spacecraft design.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Forensic ballistics involves analysis of bullets and bullet impacts to determine information of use to a court or other part of a legal system.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/ballistics] Separately from ballistics information, firearm and tool mark examinations ("ballistic fingerprinting") involve analyzing firearm, ammunition, and tool mark evidence in order to establish whether a certain firearm or tool was used in the commission of a crime.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] It is measured in inches or in millimeters.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Since metric and US customary units do not convert evenly at this scale, metric conversions of caliber measured in decimal inches are typically approximations of the precise specifications in non-metric units, and vice versa.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] In a rifled barrel, the distance is measured between opposing lands (minor diameter) or between opposing grooves (major diameter); groove measurements are common in cartridge designations originating in the United States, while land measurements are more common elsewhere in the world.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Measurements "across the grooves" are used for maximum precision because rifling and the specific caliber so measured is the result of final machining process which cuts grooves into the rough bore, leaving the "lands" behind.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Good performance requires a concentric, straight bore that accurately centers the projectile within the barrel, in preference to a "tight" fit which can be achieved even with off-center, crooked bores that cause excessive friction, fouling and an out-of-balance, wobbling projectile in flight.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] There is much variance in the use of the term "small-bore", which over the years has changed considerably, with anything under 0.577 inches (14.7 mm) considered "small-bore" prior to the mid-19th century.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] While modern firearms are generally referred to by the name of the cartridge the gun is chambered for, they are still categorized together based on bore diameter.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] For example, a firearm might be described as a "30 caliber rifle", which could accommodate any of a wide range of cartridges using a roughly 0.30 inches (7.6 mm) projectile; or as a "22 rimfire", referring to any rimfire firearms firing cartridges with a 22 caliber projectile.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] However, there can be significant differences in nominal bullet and bore dimensions, and all cartridges so "categorized" are not automatically identical in actual caliber.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] For example, 303 British firearms and projectiles are often "categorized" as ".30-caliber" alongside several dozen U.S.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] "30-caliber" cartridges despite using bullets of .310–.312-inch (7.87–7.92 mm) diameter while all U.S.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] "30-caliber" centerfire rifle cartridges use a common, standard .308-inch (7.82 mm) bullet outside diameter.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Using bullets larger than design specifications causes excessive pressures, while undersize bullets cause low pressures, insufficient muzzle velocities and fouling that will eventually lead to excessive pressures.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Makers of early cartridge arms had to invent methods of naming cartridges since no established convention existed then.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] One of the early established cartridge arms was the Spencer repeating rifle, which Union forces used in the American Civil War.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] It was named based on the chamber dimensions, rather than the bore diameter, with the earliest cartridge called the "No.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] 56 cartridge", indicating a chamber diameter of .56 in; the bore diameter varied considerably, from .52 to .54 in.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Later various derivatives were created using the same basic cartridge, but with smaller-diameter bullets; these were named by the cartridge diameter at the base and mouth.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] The 56–52, the most common of the new calibers, used a 50-cal bullet.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Other black powder-era cartridges used naming schemes that appeared similar, but measured entirely different characteristics; 45-70, 44-40, and 32-20 were designated by bullet diameter to hundredths of an inch and standard black powder charge in grains.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Optionally, the bullet weight in grains was designated, such as 45-70-405.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] This scheme was far more popular and was carried over after the advent of early smokeless powder cartridges such as the 30-30 Winchester and 22 Long.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Later developments used terms to indicate relative power, such as .44 Special and .44 Magnum.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Variations on these methods persist today, with new cartridges such as the 204 Ruger and 17 HMR (Hornady Magnum Rimfire).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Metric diameters for small arms refer to cartridge dimensions and are expressed with an "×" between the bore diameter and the length of the cartridge case; for example, the 6.5×55mm Swedish cartridge has a bore diameter of 6.5 mm and a case length of 55 mm.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] The means of measuring a rifled bore varies, and may refer to the diameter of the lands or the grooves of the rifling.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] For example, the 257 Roberts and 250 Savage both use a .257 inch projectile; both 250 Savage and 257 Roberts rifle bores have a .250 inch land diameter and .257 inch groove diameter.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] The .308 Winchester is measured across the grooves and uses a .308-in diameter (7.82-mm) bullet; the military-specification version is known as 7.62 × 51 mm NATO, so called because the bore diameter measured between the lands is 7.62 mm, and the cartridge has a case 51 mm long.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Converting a rifle to fire a different cartridge in the same bore diameter, often involves merely re-chambering the barrel to the new cartridge dimensions, if the rim diameter of the new cartridge matches that of the old cartridge.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Converting a rifle to fire a different cartridge in a different caliber and bore as what it initially was, means that the barrel of the rifle will also need to be changed.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] There are a few important factors to consider when converting a rifle to a different caliber or cartridge.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] The action of the rifle should be long enough to contain the new cartridge, the magazine should also be able to hold the new cartridge, the bolt face should be the correct diameter and the extractor the correct size to hold the head of the new cartridge.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] The most common of these caliber conversions on rifles, are usually done to change from a parent cartridge to a new cartridge based on it, like when converting a rifle to a 6.5 mm Creedmoor from a 308 Winchester on which it is based.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] The following table lists some of the commonly used calibers where both metric and US customary units are used as equivalents.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Due to variations in naming conventions, and the whims of the cartridge manufacturers, bullet diameters can vary widely from the diameter implied by the name.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] For example, a difference of 0.045 in (1.15 mm) occurs between the smallest and largest of the several cartridges designated as ".38 caliber".
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Shotguns are classed according to gauge, a related expression.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] The gauge of a shotgun refers to how many lead spheres, each with a diameter equal to that of the bore, that amounts to one pound (454 g (1.0 lb)) in weight.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] In the case of a 12-gauge (18.5 mm) shotgun, it would take 12 spheres the size of the shotgun's bore to equal a pound.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] A numerically larger gauge indicates a smaller barrel: a 20-gauge (15.6 mm) shotgun requires more spheres to equal a pound; therefore, its barrel is smaller than the 12-gauge.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] This metric is used in Russia as "caliber number": e.g., "shotgun of the 12 caliber." The 16th caliber is known as "lordly" (Russian: барский).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] While shotgun bores can be expressed in calibers (the .410 bore shotgun is measured as .410 in (10.4 mm) in diameter, unlike with rifles the actual bore diameter of a smoothbore shotgun varies significantly down the length of the barrel, with the use of chokes and back-boring.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] In the United Kingdom, "gauge" is referred to as "bore" and in the United States "bore" is referred to as "gauge", e.g. a "12-bore shotgun or 12-gauge shotgun" has a bore or gauge that can accommodate a lead sphere weighing 1/12th of a pound.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] The term caliber is used as a measure of length of artillery barrels from muzzle to breech, expressed as a multiple of the bore diameter.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] For example, a 4-inch gun of 50 calibers would have a barrel 4 in × 50 = 200 in long (written as 4" L/50 or 4"/50).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Both 14-in and 16-in navy guns were common in World War II.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] The British Royal Navy insisted on 50-cal guns on ships as it would allow 1,900 to 2,700 lb (860 to 1,220 kg) shells to travel at an initial velocity of up to 1,800 mph (2,897 km/h) to a distance of 26 mi (42 km).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Smoothbore cannon and carronade bores are designated by the weight in imperial pounds of spherical solid iron shot of diameter to fit the bore.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Standard sizes are 6, 12, 18, 24, 32, and 42 pounds, with some non-standard weights using the same scheme.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] From about the mid-17th until the mid-19th century, the measurement of the bore of large gunpowder weapons was usually expressed as the weight of its iron shot in pounds.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Iron shot was used as the standard reference because iron was the most common material used for artillery ammunition during that period, and solid spherical shot the most common form encountered.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Artillery was classified thereby into standard categories, with the 3-pounder, 4-pounder, 6-pounder, 8-pounder, 9-pounder, 12-pounder, 18-pounder, 24-pounder, and 32-pounder being the most common sizes encountered, although larger, smaller and intermediate sizes existed.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] In practice, though, significant variation occurred in the actual mass of the projectile for a given nominal shot weight.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] The country of manufacture is a significant consideration when determining bore diameters.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] For example, the French livre, until 1812, had a mass of 489.5 g (1.079 lb), whilst the contemporary English (avoirdupois) pound massed of approximately 454 g (1.001 lb).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Thus, a French 32-pounder at the Battle of Trafalgar threw a shot with 1.138 kg (2.51 lb) more mass than an English 32-pounder.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Complicating matters further, muzzle-loaded weapons require a significant gap between the sides of the tube bore and the surface of the shot.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] This is necessary so the projectile may be inserted from the mouth to the base of the tube and seated securely adjacent the propellant charge with relative ease.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] The gap, called windage, increases the size of the bore with respect to the diameter of the shot somewhere between 10% and 20% depending upon the year the tube was cast and the foundry responsible.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] The relationship between bore diameter and projectile weight was severed following the widespread adoption of rifled weapons during the latter part of the 19th century.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] Guns continued to be classed by projectile weight into the mid-20th century, particularly in British service with guns, such as the 2-pounder, 6-pounder, and 17-pounder anti-tank weapons.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/caliber] However, this value no longer definitively related to bore diameter, since projectiles were no longer simple spheres—and in any case were more often hollow shells filled with explosives rather than solid iron shot.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] A **chronograph** is a type of watch which is a stopwatch combined with a standard watch.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] A basic chronograph has hour and minute hands on the main dial to tell the time, a small seconds hand to tell that the watch is running, and a seconds hand on the main dial (usually equipped with a sweeping movement for precision) accompanied by a minutes sub dial for the stopwatch.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Another sub dial to measure the hours of the stopwatch may also be included on a chronograph.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The stopwatch can be started, stopped, and reset to zero at any time by the user by operating pushers usually placed adjacent to the crown.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] More complex chronographs often use additional complications and can have multiple sub-dials to measure more aspects of the stopwatch such as fractions of a second as well as other helpful things such as the moon phase and the local 24-hour time.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] In addition, many modern chronographs include tachymeters on the bezels for rapid calculations of speed or distance.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Louis Moinet invented the chronograph in 1816 for use in tracking astronomical objects.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Chronographs soon found use in artillery fire in the mid to late 1800s, and over times became fixtures in fields as diverse as aircraft piloting, auto racing, diving and submarining.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Since the 1980s, the term *chronograph* has also been applied to all digital watches that incorporate a stopwatch function.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The term *chronograph* comes from the Greek χρονογράφος (*khronográphos* 'time recording'), from χρόνος (*khrónos* 'time') and γράφω (*gráphō* 'to write').
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Early versions of the chronograph are the only ones that actually used any "writing": marking the dial with a small pen attached to the index so that the length of the pen mark would indicate how much time had elapsed.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The first modern chronograph was invented by Louis Moinet in 1816, solely for working with astronomical equipment.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] It was Nicolas Mathieu Rieussec who developed the first marketed chronograph at the behest of King Louis XVIII in 1821.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The King greatly enjoyed watching horse races, but wanted to know exactly how long each race lasted, so Rieussec was commissioned to invent a contraption that would do the job: as a result he developed the first ever commercialized chronograph.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Rieussec was considered the inventor of the chronograph until the Louis Moinet pocket chronograph discovery in 2013 when history was rewritten.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] In addition to inventing the chronograph, Louis Moinet is also the father of High Frequency.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] In 1816, his Compteur de Tierces timepiece beat at a rhythm of 216,000 vibrations per hour (30 Hz).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] This frequency record stood for exactly one century, before eventually being broken in 1916, after which standard chronometer frequencies returned to present-day levels (generally 5–10 Hz, or 18,000 to 36,000 vibrations per hour).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Still in perfect working order, the Compteur de Tierces is preserved at Ateliers Louis Moinet.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] In 1913, Longines created the 13.33Z, one of the first chronograph movements ever developed for a wristwatch, featuring 18 jewels, a diameter of 29 mm and height of 6 mm, and a beat rate of 18,000 vph.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] It utilized a crown that was used both for winding the watch and serving as a pusher for the chronograph.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] In 1915, Gaston Breitling produced the first chronograph with a central seconds hand and a 30-minute counter.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Later, in 1923, Gaston Breitling introduced the first chronograph with a separate pusher at 2 o'clock.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] In 1934 Willy Breitling further developed the concept of the chronograph with the addition of the second pusher at 4 o'clock.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Since then the 3-pusher chronograph design has been adopted by the entire industry.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] In 1844 Adolphe Nicole's updated version of the chronograph was the first to include a re-setting feature which now allowed successive measurements, unlike the constantly moving needle in the original chronograph.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] In the early part of the 20th century, many chronographs were sold with fixed bezels marked in order to function as a tachymeter.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] In 1958 the watch company Heuer introduced a model with a rotating bezel tachymeter for more complex calculations.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Chronographs were very popular with aviators as they allowed them to make rapid calculations and conduct precise timing.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The demand for chronographs grew along with the aviation industry in the early part of the 20th century.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] As the US exploration of outer space initially involved only test pilots, by order of President Dwight D.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Eisenhower, chronographs were on the wrists of many early astronauts.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Chronograph usage followed a similar trajectory for many fields that involve very precise and/or repeated timing around increasingly more complicated high performance machinery, automobile racing and naval submarine navigation being two examples.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Although self winding watches and clockwork have been around since the late 1700s, the automatic (self winding) chronograph was not invented until the late 1960s.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] In 1969, the watch companies Heuer, Breitling, Hamilton, and movement specialist Dubois Dépraz, developed an automatic chronograph in partnership.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] They developed this technology secretly in an effort to prevent other watchmaking houses from releasing an automatic chronograph first, namely their competition Zenith and Seiko.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] It was in Geneva and in New York that this partnership shared their first automatic chronograph with the world on March 3, 1969.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] These first automatic chronographs were labelled "chrono-matic".
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] But Zenith pre-empted them by unveiling their automatic chronograph 'El Primero' on January 10th, 1969.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Seiko also pre empted the "chrono-matic" group by releasing their first automatic chronograph in February 1969, but the model was only available in the Japanese market.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Some of the Seiko chronographs with December 1968 manufacturing date have been unearthed in Japan, pointing to an earlier domestic release, which were not known previously outside of Japan.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Many companies sell their own styles of chronographs.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] While today most chronographs are in the form of wristwatches, in the early 20th century pocket chronographs were very popular.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The term chronograph is often confused with the term chronometer.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] A simple mechanical watch, without the stopwatch functionality, can be certified a chronometer, as can a clock, for example a ship's clock, used for navigation.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The terms are not mutually exclusive either, for instance the Omega Seamaster 300M Chronograph GMT Co-Axial is also a COSC certified chronometer.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Originally the term chronograph was mainly used in connection with artillery and the velocity of missiles.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The chronograph's main function is to allow a comparison of observation between a time base and, before the electronic stopwatch was invented, a permanent recording of the observer's findings.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] For example, one of the first applications of the chronograph was to record the time elapsed during horse races.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Some more important uses of the chronograph include the Langley Chronograph, which is used by the US Navy to record, calculate, and analyse data given off by aeroplane launching catapults.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Another famous usage of the chronograph was during NASA's Apollo missions to the moon, when each astronaut was equipped with a fully functioning chronograph, the Omega Speedmaster; in one instance, a Bulova chronograph was used.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Chronographs are routinely used to record heart beats within hospitals, calculate speed and/or distance on athletic fields, or even as simple timers in kitchens.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Chronographs can be extremely complicated devices, but they all have the basic function of telling time, as they are watches, and of displaying elapsed time.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Rieussec's chronograph was fairly simple.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] It was composed of two faces, a top and bottom face.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The bottom face held a pool of ink, while the upper had a pen-like needle attached to it.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] When activated, the upper face pushed down on the lower face, while revolving around a central axis, which pulled the needle.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] This dragged the ink, in a circular fashion, recording the time elapsed by the line of ink that the motion created.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] There was room left for improvement, because Rieussec's chronograph was not easily ready for multiple uses.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] This paved the way for the hundreds of patents that have been handed out to people for updating and upgrading this device.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Automatic, non-digital chronographs do not require a battery, because the arm or wrist of the wearer creates kinetic energy, which results in the total energy source needed for this device to work.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Throughout the day, while the wearer of the watch is walking, the swinging motion of his arm forces a semicircular rotor to turn on a pivot within the watch.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The rotor is attached to a ratchet that winds the mainspring in the watch, so that it is ready for use at all times.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The modern day chronograph works by pushing a start button, normally located at the two o'clock position, to begin recording time, and by pushing the same button to stop the recording.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] When the button is pushed to start the recording, a series of three (in more complicated and more precise chronographs there are more wheels) train wheels start turning.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The smallest has a revolution time of one second, the next sixty seconds, and the final one has a revolution time of sixty minutes.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The three train wheels interact with one another and record how long it has been since the start button has been activated.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] In addition to the start button, it also features a reset button normally located at the four o'clock position.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] When the reset button is pushed the chronograph hand will reset back to zero.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Tachymeter bezels are a complication that allows rapid calculations of speed or distance.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Rotating bezels allow for more complex calculations or repeated calculations without requiring a reset of the timer.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The original chronographs that Rieussec invented were called tape chronographs.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] They consisted of a tape that was constantly being dragged along at a controlled speed.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] When activated, a pen would be pushed onto the tape and begin recording until deactivated.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Specialized chronographs are used by deep sea and scuba divers.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] While basic functionality is the same as other chronographs, diving models have longer and more practical straps to wear over equipment, are made to be waterproof to deeper depths, have more rounded corners to prevent catching and luminous dials for reading in the murky depths.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Metered bezels: Many chronographs have a bezel, that is either fixed or can rotate, around the outside of the dial that is marked to specific scales to allow rapid calculations.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] While any wristwatch can have a bezel, the chronograph stop start feature, as well as the rotation of the bezel, allows more complex calculations or repeated measurements for a series of calculations.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The most popular meter is for tachymeter readings: a simple scale that allows rapid calculations of speed.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Other bezels feature telemeter scale, for distance.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The watchmaking company Breitling offers a model with a rotating bezel, in conjunction with another, fixed, meter on the dial, scaled for use as a slide rule for more complex calculations.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Flyback chronographs have a timing hand that can be rapidly reset, or *flyback*, to zero.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Ordinarily the sweep second hand is stopped to record the time and started again at that spot on the dial, or reset by spinning the second hand all the way to zero again, clockwise.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The flyback allows a reading and a quick reset—a counterclockwise flyback—for the next measurement to start at zero.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] A *rattrapante*, sometimes called a *double chronograph*, has multiple second hands, at least one of which can be stopped and started independently.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] When not activated, the second hands travel together, one under the other, to appear as just one second hand.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] A *tourbillon*, although not strictly limited to chronographs, is an escapement set in a cage and placed in a rotating balance in order to minimize the effects of gravity on the escapement and increase precision.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Because chronograph escapements are generally larger and connect with more complications, a tourbillon in a chronograph will differ from a tourbillon in a more simple timepiece.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Other types of modern-day chronographs are the *automatic chronograph* and the *digital chronograph*.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The automatic chronograph depends solely on kinetic energy as its power source, while the digital chronograph is much like the common stopwatch and uses a battery to gain power, as well as quartz for timing.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Other, more specific, types of chronographs include split second chronographs, tide chronographs, and asthmometer chronographs.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] Each of these chronographs has an added feature that sets them apart.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The *telemeter chronograph* allows the user to approximately measure the distance to an event that can be both seen and heard (e.g. a lightning bolt or a torpedo strike) using the speed of sound.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The user starts the chronograph (stopwatch) at the instant the event is seen, and stops timing at the instant the event is heard.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The seconds hand will point to the distance measured on a scale, usually around the edge of the face.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/chronograph] The scale can be defined in any unit of distance, but miles or kilometers are most practical and commonplace.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] A **drop** or **droplet** is a small column of liquid, bounded completely or almost completely by free surfaces.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] A drop may form when liquid accumulates at the end of a tube or other surface boundary, producing a hanging drop called a pendant drop.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Drops may also be formed by the condensation of a vapor or by atomization of a larger mass of solid.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Water vapor will condense into droplets depending on the temperature.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The temperature at which droplets form is called the dew point.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Liquid forms drops because it exhibits surface tension.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] A simple way to form a drop is to allow liquid to flow slowly from the lower end of a vertical tube of small diameter.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The surface tension of the liquid causes the liquid to hang from the tube, forming a pendant.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] When the drop exceeds a certain size it is no longer stable and detaches itself.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The falling liquid is also a drop held together by surface tension.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Some substances that appear to be solid, can be shown to instead be extremely viscous liquids, because they form drops and display droplet behavior.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] In the famous pitch drop experiments, pitch – a substance somewhat like solid bitumen – is shown to be a liquid in this way.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Pitch in a funnel slowly forms droplets, each droplet taking about 10 years to form and break off.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] In the pendant drop test, a drop of liquid is suspended from the end of a tube or by any surface by surface tension.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The force due to surface tension is proportional to the length of the boundary between the liquid and the tube, with the proportionality constant usually denoted $\gamma$ .
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] where α is the angle of contact with the tube's front surface, and *g* is the acceleration due to gravity.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The limit of this formula, as α goes to 90°, gives the maximum weight of a pendant drop for a liquid with a given surface tension, $\gamma$ .
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] This relationship is the basis of a convenient method of measuring surface tension, commonly used in the petroleum industry.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] More sophisticated methods are available to take account of the developing shape of the pendant as the drop grows.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] These methods are used if the surface tension is unknown.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The drop adhesion to a solid can be divided into two categories: lateral adhesion and normal adhesion.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Lateral adhesion resembles friction (though tribologically lateral adhesion is a more accurate term) and refers to the force required to slide a drop on the surface, namely the force to detach the drop from its position on the surface only to translate it to another position on the surface.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Normal adhesion is the adhesion required to detach a drop from the surface in the normal direction, namely the force to cause the drop to fly off from the surface.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The measurement of both adhesion forms can be done with the Centrifugal Adhesion Balance (CAB).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The CAB uses a combination of centrifugal and gravitational forces to obtain any ratio of lateral and normal forces.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] For example, it can apply a normal force at zero lateral force for the drop to fly off away from the surface in the normal direction or it can induce a lateral force at zero normal force (simulating zero gravity).
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The term **droplet** is a diminutive form of 'drop' – and as a guide is typically used for liquid particles of less than 500 μm diameter.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] In spray application, droplets are usually described by their perceived size (i.e., diameter) whereas the dose (or number of infective particles in the case of biopesticides) is a function of their volume.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] This increases by a cubic function relative to diameter; thus, a 50 μm droplet represents a dose in 65 pl and a 500 μm drop represents a dose in 65 nanolitres.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] A droplet with a diameter of 3 mm has a terminal velocity of approximately 8 m/s.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Drops smaller than 1 mm in diameter will attain 95% of their terminal velocity within 2 m.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] But above this size the distance to get to terminal velocity increases sharply.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] An example is a drop with a diameter of 2 mm that may achieve this at 5.6 m.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Due to the different refractive index of water and air, refraction and reflection occur on the surfaces of raindrops, leading to rainbow formation.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The major source of sound when a droplet hits a liquid surface is the resonance of excited bubbles trapped underwater.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] These oscillating bubbles are responsible for most liquid sounds, such as running water or splashes, as they actually consist of many drop-liquid collisions.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Reducing the surface tension of a body of liquid makes possible to reduce or prevent noise due to droplets falling into it.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] This would involve adding soap, detergent or a similar substance to water.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The reduced surface tension reduces the noise from dripping.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The classic shape associated with a drop (with a pointy end in its upper side) comes from the observation of a droplet clinging to a surface.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The shape of a drop falling through a gas is actually more or less spherical for drops less than 2 mm in diameter.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Larger drops tend to be flatter on the bottom part due to the pressure of the gas they move through.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] As a result, as drops get larger, a concave depression forms which leads to the eventual breakup of the drop.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The capillary length is a length scaling factor that relates gravity, density, and surface tension, and is directly responsible for the shape a droplet for a specific fluid will take.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The capillary length stems from the Laplace pressure, using the radius of the droplet.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Using the capillary length we can define microdrops and macrodrops.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Microdrops are droplets with radius smaller than the capillary length, where the shape of the droplet is governed by surface tension and they form a more or less spherical cap shape.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] If a droplet has a radius larger than the capillary length, they are known as macrodrops and the gravitational forces will dominate.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Macrodrops will be 'flattened' by gravity and the height of the droplet will be reduced.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Raindrop sizes typically range from 0.5 mm to 4 mm, with size distributions quickly decreasing past diameters larger than 2–2.5 mm.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] Scientists traditionally thought that the variation in the size of raindrops was due to collisions on the way down to the ground.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] In 2009, French researchers succeeded in showing that the distribution of sizes is due to the drops' interaction with air, which deforms larger drops and causes them to fragment into smaller drops, effectively limiting the largest raindrops to about 6 mm diameter.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] However, drops up to 10 mm (equivalent in volume to a sphere of radius 4.5 mm) are theoretically stable and could be levitated in a wind tunnel.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] The largest recorded raindrop was 8.8 mm in diameter, located at the base of a cumulus congestus cloud in the vicinity of Kwajalein Atoll in July 1999.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] A raindrop of identical size was detected over northern Brazil in September 1995.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] In medicine, this property is used to create droppers and IV infusion sets which have a standardized diameter, in such a way that 1 millilitre is equivalent to 20 drops.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/droplet] When smaller amounts are necessary (such as paediatrics), microdroppers or paediatric infusion sets are used, in which 1 millilitre = 60 microdrops.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Eye protection are typically separated into categories based on the style of eye wear and the hazard they are designed to reduce.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] There categories include: spectacles with side protection; goggles; welding helmet; welding hand shields; non-rigid helmets (hoods); face shield; and respirator face pieces.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Safety glasses or spectacles, although often used as a catch-all term for all types of eye protection, specifically refers to protective equipment that closely resembles common eye wear.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] To meet most national standards, spectacles must include side shields to reduce the ability of debris to get behind the lenses from the side.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Safety glasses can often mount insert frames to mount prescription corrective lenses for users with suboptimal vision.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Such insert frames are mounted behind the protective lens.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] In some applications, regular eye wear, if manufactured from high-impact materials, can be worn with removable side shields.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Oversized spectacles are also manufactured, designed to sit over the user's normal eye wear.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Goggles are forms of protective eyewear that enclose the eye area in order to prevent particulates, infectious fluids, or chemicals from striking the eyes.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Goggles come in two styles, eyecup goggles, and cover goggles.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Eyecup goggles completely cover the eye socket to give all-round protection.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] They have adjustable or elasticized headbands and often are equipped with ventilation ports to allow air in and prevent fogging.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] For example, swimming goggles protect the eyes from salt or chlorine.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Cover goggles are designed to be worn over eye wear.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Like eyecup goggles, they have adjustable or elasticized headbands and are equipped with direct or indirect ventilation ports to allow air in and prevent fogging.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] While both models keep out large particles, indirect-vented goggles are better at keeping out liquids and dusts.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] A welding helmet is a type of headgear used when performing certain types of welding to protect the eyes, face and neck from flash burn, ultraviolet light, sparks, infrared light, and heat.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] A welding hand shield is a metal plate containing the same protective lens as a welding helmet with a handle on the bottom, intended to be held up in front of the face while working.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Hoods (or non-rigid helmets) come with impact-resistant windows usually made of plastic or similar material.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] An air-supply system may also be incorporated.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Hoods are made of non-rigid material for use in confined spaces and of collapsible construction for convenience in carrying and storing.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] A face shield is a device used to protect wearer's entire face (or part of it) from hazards such as impact, splash, heat, or glare.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] With face shields, as with welding helmets and hand shields, the user is periodically lifting and lowering the visor.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] To protect the eyes when the visor is lifted, spectacles should be worn underneath.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] A respirator is a device designed to protect the wearer from inhaling particulate matter, including airborne microorganisms, fumes, vapours and gases.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Insects like flies, bees, and wasps can fly at high speeds and come into contact with a person's eyes.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Their wings or stingers can cause irritation or even scratch the cornea, which can be painful and potentially cause long-term damage.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Small projectiles and fragments generated from processes like grinding, machining, or tool or part breakage under strain (e.g., when torque is applied with hand tools, power tools, impact wrenches, or cheater bars) can have the potential to penetrate some types of protective eye-wear.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] In the United States the ANSI/ISEA Z87.1-2020 standard is used to certify protective eye-wear which is capable of protecting from these hazards.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Debris such as dust, dirt, and small rocks can be picked up by the wind and fly into one's eyes.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] This can cause discomfort and potentially lead to a corneal abrasion or infection.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun can also harm a person's eyes.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Prolonged exposure to UV rays can cause cataracts, macular degeneration, and other eye conditions that can lead to vision loss.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] A large percentage of eye injuries are caused by direct contact with chemicals.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] These injuries often result from an inappropriate choice of personal protective equipment that allows a chemical substance to enter from around or under protective eye equipment.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Serious and irreversible damage can occur when chemical substances contact the eyes in the form of splash, mists, vapors, or fumes.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] When working with or around chemicals, it is important to know the location of emergency eyewash stations and how to access them with restricted vision.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] When fitted and worn correctly, goggles protect your eyes from hazardous substances.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] A face shield may be required in areas where workers are exposed to severe chemical hazards.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] The human eye is sensitive to intense light because it damages the retina and can even blind the individual.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] There are many different types of eye protection against light suited for different applications.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] The most common forms of eye protection against light are sunglasses.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] These primarily protect against UV light from the sun and help increase visibility in bright conditions.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] They often tend to be fashionable as well as practical.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Laser protection eyewear will filter out a particular (or small range of) wavelength(s), customized to the laser being viewed.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Laser protection eye wear is particularly important because of the extremely high intensity of laser light.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Welding glass protects against glare and flying sparks.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] It is a more extreme implementation of the same idea as sunglasses, suited to the more intense light generated during welding.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Arc welding goggles must be much darker than blowtorch goggles.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Shades 12, 13, and 14 welding glass must be used to stare directly at the sun or a solar eclipse.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] These higher index shades are suitable for arc welding and therefore are suitable for solar viewing.
[src:authorized-protective-eyewear-list/eye-protection] Sunglasses will not provide sufficient protection.
